  "meta": {
    "title": "Daoism",
    "description": "Chinese Daoism is a Chinese philosophy of natural practice structured around a normative focus on d&agrave;o (&#36947; path, way). This naturalist philosophical project treated d&agrave;o as a structure of natural possibility for living beings. Unlike similar Western naturalisms, e.g., pragmatism, Daoism's foil was contemporary: the Confucian-Mohist ( Ru-Mo ) dialectic about human (&#20154; r&eacute;n human, social) d&agrave;o . Daoism's critique of Ru-Mo debate concerns the role of natural (&#22825; ti&#257;n sky-nature) d&agrave;o vs human d&agrave;o (socially constructed guidance). Daoism's founding personages ( Laozi and Zhuangzi ) did not coin their \"-ism.\" The two Classical texts, credited to their titled masters (&#23376; z&#464; son), emerged during the Classical period (5 to 3 C. BC ). Each reflected skeptically on the Confucian-Mohist dispute about the correct socio-political d&agrave;o . Historians first coined the collective category \"Daoist\" (&#36947;&#23478; d&agrave;oji&#257; school of d&agrave;o ) during the Han (2 C BC to 2 C), There are inconclusive hints of their having shared a philosophical project in the two writings. The philosophical project was to conceive of norms (permissibility) as metaphorical path -like structures ( d&agrave;o s) of natural possibility. Its signal axiom was that the structure changed constantly as new things (and d&agrave;o s) emerged. All such natural d&agrave;o s are guides for the behavior (&#34892; x&iacute;ng walking) of things (&#29289; w&ugrave; natural kinds). We, humans and some other living things, learn behaviors in the ways we learn to walk following paths. Confucians championed human paths (&#20154; r&eacute;n &#36947; d&agrave;o ): historical social structures consisting of practices (&#20107; sh&igrave; affair, business) by named role players, a morality typified by ceremonial ritual (&#31150; l&#464; decorum). Daoists favored wider natural ( ti&#257;n ) d&agrave;o s of the cosmos (&#22825;&#22320; ti&#257;nd&igrave; heaven & earth) of which all the \"ten-thousand natural kinds \" (&#29289; w&ugrave; things) are parts. Living things occupy the space between heaven and earth (&#22825;&#19979; ti&#257;nxi&agrave; the-world-under heaven) and have potential (&#21487; k&#283; permissible or possible) paths available for their behavior ( x&iacute;ng ). These paths result from the natural distribution of existing things in the environment. The implicit axiom of D&agrave;o ism is there are permissible paths in the natural world. Nature gives us virtuosity (&#24503; d&eacute; virtue, excellence) in finding, learning, and following these paths of possibility. Learning from the past is a permissible natural way to acquire this virtuosity . However, it is unlikely that our current evolved social practices exhaust the permissible possibilities of learning about natural d&agrave;o . We can reform social practices, but in doing so, we rely on ways of choosing among d&agrave;o s guiding that reform. This is a key insight drawn from the Confucian-Mohist dispute. Mozi's proposed reform process depended on an allegedly natural, meta- d&agrave;o of measuring utility (&#21033; l&igrave; benefit, harvest). This doesn't make reform impossible or incoherent but initiates a regress of choosing ways while still in momentum along a way. We measure utility using existing concepts, ways of identifying utility and prefer it to other ways of improving our current social d&agrave;o s. The result is Daoism's version of normative autonomy, one that starts from normative naturalism. It mimics mild skepticism. No matter how we learn and choose, there may be some possibilities we overlook. Its departure from Mohism lies in rejecting Mozi's assumption that nature ( ti&#257;n ) d&agrave;o is biased to benefit humans. Nature is neutral toward the ways of life \"under the sky.\" Claiming to know nature's intent is cognitively na&iuml;ve. A wholistic path structure affords us permissible/possible 4-dimensional future behaviors . That is natural D&agrave;o. It is how things have and can unfold, the \"how\" of our 4-dimensional past (and future). D&agrave;o is how natural kinds are born (&#29983; sh&#275;ng birth, life)--come to exist (&#26377; y&#466;u have ), change, evolve and eventually disappear (&#28961; w&uacute; lack). Western \"things\" (parts of the world picked out by noun phrases) are divided in China into natural kinds (&#29289; w&ugrave; ), artifacts (&#22120; q&igrave; tools, utensils), and practices ( sh&igrave; ). Natural kinds have internal d&agrave;o s (called &#29702; l&#464; lanes-in-jade) that interacts with external road structures. Our human internal d&agrave;o ( l&#464; ) makes learning (&#23416; xu&eacute; study, practice) and practiced virtuosity possible. Individually and collectively, we learn and practice behaviors. Importantly, d&agrave;o, the structure of natural probability is more like a map than a formula, rule or law. It is like a GPS of life that gives us alternatives and suggests different paths we can choose from: fastest, most scenic, calmest, etc. It consists of all the hows of nature but explains only when made into a map which humans can learn to read. Modern Daoists embrace science but venerate (astro-physical) nature . Science is our best current social d&agrave;o for understanding nature's structure, certainly better than the classical Yin-Yang school's tables of correlation. However, natural d&agrave;o does not consist of commands or prohibitions, but of opportunities. D&agrave;o permeates the space-time cosmos, is everywhere forever. It comes to have its structure of itself (&#33258;&#28982; z&igrave;r&aacute;n naturally, spontaneously, lit. self-make-so, realize from here). Chinese Daoism is holistic or monist in the sense of the whole being prior to its parts. D&agrave;o and the cosmos exist (&#26377; y&#466;u have, being) and \"the ten thousand things and I\" are born, emerge from as natural parts of cosmic d&agrave;o (Laozi Ch. 1, Zhuangzi 2:9). D&agrave;o unfolds into the future as every part self-realizes ( z&igrave;r&aacute;n ) some possible ( k&#283; ) d&agrave;o guiding how it walks (&#34892; x&iacute;ng ) into the future. Early phase Daoists, Hui Shi, Shen Dao and Laozi's Daode Jing implicitly rejected parthood, suggesting an absolute, Parmenidean, monism. Shen Dao's version was of a fatalistic \"block universe\" in which nothing really happens. Priority monism characterizes the bulk of the Laozi and Zhuangzi . All the proper parts of y&#466;u , the ten-thousand natural kinds, have d&agrave;o s which are proper parts of the larger daos . The ultimate d&agrave;o is a cosmic network of possible histories of possible thing-parts. Dao is therefore constantly changing as things realize their possibilities. The unrealized paths recede into the past. Controversies emerged within philosophical Daoism and between it and rival philosophical agendas. We elaborate on these and the implications of Daoist naturalism for linguistics, cosmology, metaphysics, knowledge and ethics in the sections below. Religious Daoism is a separate topic treated here .",
    "version": "1.0.0",
